{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17617129","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17617129"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:10:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:10:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16454"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16454","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16454"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0,0.74,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9145"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75115"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9145","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9145"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16454"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60623"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"8511"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21719"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21724"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75115"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe blood-brain barrier is formed by specialised endothelial cells connected by tight junctions. This barrier plays a crucial role in maintaining central nervous system homeostasis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the permeability characteristics of the blood-brain barrier?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Allows charged, hydrophilic molecules to pass through readily","Prevents passage of all molecules into brain tissue","Permits lipophilic molecules while restricting hydrophilic molecules","Facilitates transport of all therapeutic drugs","Blocks passage of every protein molecule"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe blood-brain barrier is a highly selective semipermeable border of endothelial cells that prevents solutes in the circulating blood from non-selectively crossing into the extracellular fluid of the central nervous system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPermits lipophilic molecules while restricting hydrophilic molecules\u003C/strong\u003E is correct. The blood-brain barrier preferentially allows passage of small, lipid-soluble molecules through passive diffusion while restricting the passage of large or water-soluble molecules. This is why many CNS-active drugs are designed to be lipophilic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAllows charged, hydrophilic molecules to pass through readily\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The opposite is true - hydrophilic molecules have difficulty crossing the blood-brain barrier due to the tight junctions between endothelial cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevents passage of all molecules into brain tissue\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Essential nutrients, gases like oxygen, and some molecules necessary for brain function can cross the barrier through specific transport mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitates transport of all therapeutic drugs\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While some substances are actively transported across the barrier, many drugs cannot cross it at all, which presents a challenge in developing CNS medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks passage of every protein molecule\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While the blood-brain barrier does restrict most protein passage, some specific proteins can cross through receptor-mediated transcytosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The blood-brain barrier selectively restricts passage of substances between blood and brain tissue, primarily allowing lipophilic molecules to pass while blocking hydrophilic ones.","Tight junctions between endothelial cells are a key structural component of the blood-brain barrier.","The blood-brain barrier helps maintain brain homeostasis by regulating ion concentrations and preventing entry of potentially harmful substances."],"references":["Daneman R, Prat A. The blood-brain barrier. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2015 Jan 5;7(1):a020412. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a020412. PMID: 25561720; PMCID: PMC4292164.","Alahmari A. Blood-Brain Barrier Overview: Structural and Functional Correlation. Neural Plast. 2021 Dec 6;2021:6564585. doi: 10.1155/2021/6564585. PMID: 34912450; PMCID: PMC8668349.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60623"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16454"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60623","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60623"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T22:52:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T22:57:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9145"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75115"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"